<Layout title="dojo-n-speed contributions — Ian Bragg">
  <h1>dojo-n-speed contributions</h1>
  <p class="tagline">Production contributions to a DefectDojo fork — LLM-augmented features for security finding management, multi-SCM abstraction, governance-aware infrastructure.</p>

  <div class="signals">
    <span class="signal">Status: shipped (and ongoing)</span>
    <span class="signal">Django · Python · LLMs in production · AppSec</span>
  </div>

  <h2>Context</h2>
  <p>
    DefectDojo is the dominant open-source platform for managing application
    security findings — vulnerability triage, deduplication, lifecycle,
    integrations across scanners. A team I work with maintains a fork
    tailored to high-rigor deployments. My contributions sit at the
    intersection of the application backend, developer experience, and the
    LLM-augmentation surface.
  </p>

  <h2>Features shipped</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Multi-SCM abstraction layer.</strong> A pluggable helper that
      generates correct deep-links from a finding to the offending code,
      regardless of whether the source lives on GitHub, Gitea, Bitbucket, or
      Azure DevOps. Replaces hard-coded GitHub-only handling in several call
      sites.</li>
    <li><strong>VS Code integration.</strong> One-click <code>vscode://</code>
      handlers from findings → opens the file at the right line in the
      reviewer's editor, including in air-gapped / code-server deployments.</li>
    <li><strong>Governance-aware infrastructure.</strong> Tooling for
      filter-branch / commit-history anonymization so the fork can be
      mirrored cleanly between collaborator accounts without leaking
      contributor metadata that doesn't belong in the public surface.</li>
    <li><strong>LLM-augmented triage (in development).</strong> Claude-driven
      summarization and clustering of findings to reduce reviewer fatigue
      on noisy scan output.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why it matters to a hiring manager</h2>
  <p>
    Shipping AppSec features in Django at a real production cadence, against
    real-world constraints (multi-SCM portability, compliance environments,
    contributor governance) is concrete evidence of "can do anything
    software" — not just AI. It's also the closest analog on this profile to
    the day-to-day work at companies like Snyk, Veracode, HiddenLayer, and
    the security teams at AI labs.
  </p>
</Layout>
